<Layout title="Gastrointestinal & Hepatic Assessment Tools" description="Gastrointestinal and hepatic assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Gastrointestinal &amp; Hepatic</div>
  <h1>Gastrointestinal &amp; Hepatic Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Scoring systems for liver disease, GI bleeding, pancreatitis, inflammatory bowel disease, and swallowing assessment.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Child-Pugh Score</strong> — Liver disease severity: Bilirubin, Albumin, PT/INR, Ascites, Encephalopathy. Classes A (5–6, mild), B (7–9, moderate), C (10–15, severe); guides transplant listing and procedural risk.</li>
      <li><strong>MELD Score (Model for End-Stage Liver Disease)</strong> — Bilirubin, creatinine, and INR-based mortality prediction for cirrhosis. MELD &gt;20 indicates significant 3-month mortality risk; guides transplant prioritization.</li>
      <li><strong>Glasgow-Blatchford Score</strong> — Pre-endoscopy risk stratification for upper GI bleeding: blood urea, hemoglobin, systolic BP, pulse, presentation features. Score 0 = low risk (safe for outpatient).</li>
      <li><strong>Rockall Score</strong> — Post-endoscopy upper GI bleed re-bleeding and mortality risk: age, shock, comorbidity, endoscopic diagnosis, stigmata. Score ≤2 = low rebleed risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Ranson Criteria</strong> — Pancreatitis severity at admission (5 criteria) and at 48 hours (6 criteria). Score ≥3 indicates severe pancreatitis requiring ICU-level care.</li>
      <li><strong>BISAP Score</strong> — Five-item pancreatitis mortality predictor: BUN &gt;25, Impaired mental status, SIRS criteria, Age &gt;60, Pleural effusion. Score ≥3 associated with significant mortality.</li>
      <li><strong>Alvarado Score (MANTRELS)</strong> — Appendicitis clinical probability: Migration of pain, Anorexia, Nausea/vomiting, RLQ tenderness, Rebound tenderness, Elevated temperature, Leukocytosis, Left shift. Score 7–10 = high probability.</li>
      <li><strong>APRI (AST-to-Platelet Ratio Index)</strong> — Non-invasive liver fibrosis surrogate: AST/upper limit of normal ÷ platelet count × 100. APRI &gt;0.7 suggests significant fibrosis; &gt;1.0 suggests cirrhosis.</li>
      <li><strong>Harvey-Bradshaw Index</strong> — Simplified Crohn's disease activity index: general wellbeing, abdominal pain, number of liquid stools, abdominal mass, complications. Score &lt;5 = remission.</li>
      <li><strong>Mayo Score (Ulcerative Colitis)</strong> — Disease activity for UC: stool frequency, rectal bleeding, mucosal appearance, physician global assessment. Score 0–12; ≤2 = remission.</li>
      <li><strong>Wexner Score (Fecal Incontinence)</strong> — 30-point scale measuring fecal incontinence severity and lifestyle impact across five stool types and social function domains.</li>
      <li><strong>Constipation Assessment Scale (CAS)</strong> — Eight-item tool assessing abdominal distension, change in gas passage, frequency, oozing, fullness, rectal pressure, rectal pain, and stool amount.</li>
      <li><strong>Bristol Stool Chart</strong> — Seven-type classification of stool consistency from Type 1 (hard lumps) to Type 7 (watery). Types 3–4 are normal; guides bowel management documentation.</li>
      <li><strong>DOSS (Dysphagia Outcome and Severity Scale)</strong> — Seven-level dysphagia severity scale from Level 1 (severe) to Level 7 (normal) used in speech-language pathology and nursing documentation.</li>
      <li><strong>EAT-10 (Eating Assessment Tool)</strong> — 10-item patient self-report of swallowing difficulty symptoms. Score ≥3 indicates swallowing problem requiring clinical evaluation.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
